# Mobile-First Development Rules

## Core Principle
**Always design and develop mobile-first.** Start with mobile styles as the base, then enhance for larger screens using Tailwind's responsive breakpoints.

## Why Mobile-First?
- **Performance**: Mobile-first CSS loads faster on mobile devices
- **Progressive Enhancement**: Start with essential features, add enhancements for larger screens
- **Better UX**: Ensures mobile users get a great experience first
- **Easier Maintenance**: Base styles are simpler, enhancements are additive

## Tailwind Breakpoints
Tailwind uses mobile-first breakpoints. Base styles apply to mobile, then override/enhance for larger screens:
- **Base (no prefix)**: Mobile (default, < 640px)
- **`sm:`**: Small screens (≥ 640px)
- **`md:`**: Medium screens (≥ 768px)
- **`lg:`**: Large screens (≥ 1024px)
- **`xl:`**: Extra large screens (≥ 1280px)
- **`2xl:`**: 2X large screens (≥ 1536px)

## Patterns

### Layout
✅ **Do**: Start with mobile layout, enhance for desktop
```tsx
// Mobile-first: column on mobile, row on larger screens
<div className="flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-4">
  <div>Content 1</div>
  <div>Content 2</div>
</div>
```

❌ **Don't**: Start with desktop layout

### Typography
✅ **Do**: Start with smaller text, increase for larger screens
```tsx
<h1 className="text-xl sm:text-2xl md:text-3xl lg:text-4xl">Responsive Heading</h1>
```

### Spacing
✅ **Do**: Use smaller spacing on mobile, increase for larger screens
```tsx
<div className="p-4 sm:p-6 md:p-8">Content with responsive padding</div>
```

### Visibility
✅ **Do**: Hide/show elements based on screen size
```tsx
{/* Mobile-only */}
<div className="block sm:hidden">Mobile Menu</div>
{/* Desktop-only */}
<div className="hidden sm:block">Desktop Menu</div>
```

### Grid and Columns
✅ **Do**: Single column on mobile, multiple on larger screens
```tsx
<div className="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
  {items.map(item => <Item key={item.id} />)}
</div>
```

## Component Examples

### Dialog/Modal
```tsx
// Mobile-first dialog: full screen on mobile, centered on desktop
<DialogContent className="w-full h-full sm:w-auto sm:h-auto sm:max-w-lg">
  <DialogHeader className="text-center sm:text-left">
    <DialogTitle>Title</DialogTitle>
  </DialogHeader>
  <DialogFooter className="flex-col-reverse sm:flex-row sm:justify-end">
    <Button variant="outline">Cancel</Button>
    <Button>Confirm</Button>
  </DialogFooter>
</DialogContent>
```

### Navigation
```tsx
// Mobile: hamburger menu, Desktop: horizontal nav
<nav className="flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-4">
  <button className="sm:hidden">☰</button>
  <div className="hidden sm:flex gap-4">
    <Link href="/">Home</Link>
    <Link href="/about">About</Link>
  </div>
</nav>
```

## Testing
1. **Test on mobile devices first** - Use browser dev tools mobile emulation
2. **Verify touch targets** - Ensure buttons/links are at least 44x44px
3. **Check text readability** - Ensure text is readable without zooming
4. **Test landscape orientation** - Verify layouts work in both orientations
5. **Progressive enhancement** - Verify core functionality works without JavaScript

## Common Mistakes
❌ **Don't**: Use desktop-first breakpoints `flex-row max-md:flex-col`
❌ **Don't**: Assume desktop is the default `lg:flex lg:gap-4` (missing mobile base)
❌ **Don't**: Ignore mobile touch targets `<button className="w-6 h-6">×</button>` (too small)

## Best Practices
- **Start with mobile styles** - Write base styles for mobile first
- **Use responsive utilities** - Leverage Tailwind's responsive prefixes
- **Test frequently** - Check mobile view during development
- **Progressive enhancement** - Add features for larger screens, don't remove for mobile
- **Touch-friendly** - Ensure interactive elements are easy to tap
- **Readable text** - Use appropriate font sizes for mobile screens
- **Performance** - Optimize images and assets for mobile networks

